      "content": [
        { "type": "title", "value": "Greetings & Registers" },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Cantonese has different ways to say 'hello' depending on how formal the situation is. For most formal or neutral situations, we use <strong>你好</strong> (nei5 hou2). However, among friends, it is much more common to use <strong>哈囉</strong> (haa1 lo3) or ask <strong>點呀？</strong> (dim2 aa3?), which means 'What's up?' or 'How's it going?'."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "你好",
          "romanization": "nei5 hou2",
          "translation": "Hello (Formal/Neutral)"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "點呀？",
          "romanization": "dim2 aa3?",
          "translation": "What's up? / How's it going?"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "We also have specific greetings for different times of day. <strong>早晨</strong> (zou2 san1) is the ubiquitous 'Good morning'. For afternoon and evening, we use <strong>午安</strong> (ng5 on1) and <strong>晚安</strong> (maan5 on1), though these are more formal and less common in casual speech than 'zou2 san1'."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "早晨",
          "romanization": "zou2 san1",
          "translation": "Good morning"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "午安",
          "romanization": "ng5 on1",
          "translation": "Good afternoon"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "晚安",
          "romanization": "maan5 on1",
          "translation": "Good evening"
        }
      ]
    },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "2.1.2" },
    { "type": "unscramble", "exerciseId": "2.1.3" },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "2.1.4" },
